******
[1] Thailand
Date: Thu 7 Jul 2011
Source: The ASTV Manager Online [in Thai, trans. Mod.SCM, edited]
http://www.manager.co.th/Local/ViewNews.aspx?NewsID=9540000083310


Over 100 cases of dengue infection were reported in Maha Sarakham
province. Recently, there were 155 cases treated at Maha Sarakham
hospital and other government health centers. The highest number of
cases was reported in Muang district (34 cases), Phayakkhaphum Phisai
(29), and Borabue (17). The trend of the dengue outbreak is still
increasing because of the rainy season and hot weather.

Dr Suriya Ratanaparinya, Maha Sarakham Provincial health officer, has
ordered health officers and public health volunteers to clean up the
environment and spray to eradicate mosquito larvae.

--
Communicated by:
PRO/MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[Maha Sarakham is one of the provinces in the northeastern region of
Thailand. In 2010, a total of 778 cases and 2 fatalities due to dengue
infection were reported in the province. Among these, 394 cases and
one death were attributed to dengue fever (DF), 375 cases and one
death were attributed to dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF), and 9 cases
were attributed to dengue shock syndrome (DSS).

According to the newswire above, there were 155 dengue cases reported
in Maha Sarakham province from January 2011 to 7 Jul 2011. The total
number of cases due to dengue infection in the 1st 6 months of 2010
was a little higher than that of in 2011; there were 174 cases (103 DF
cases, 67 DHF cases, and 4 DSS cases).

For maps showing Thailand's regions, see
http://www.thailand-map.net/thailand_provinces/; for provinces, see
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provinces_of_Thailand. For the
interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Thailand with links to other
recent ProMED-mail and PRO/MBDS postings, see
http://healthmap.org/r/03Jk. - Mod.SCM]

******
[2] Reports from various countries:
Latin America
---
- Brazil (Sergipe state). 15 Jul 2011. This year [2011], up to 11 Jul
[2011], 2 [dengue] deaths are confirmed and others are under
investigation to determine if dengue [virus infections] were the cause
of death. The state Secretariat of Health registered 1063 confirmed
cases of the disease between the month of January and 11 Jul [2011],
of the 3821 suspected [dengue] cases reported in 75 municipalities in
Sergipe.
http://www.infonet.com.br/saude/ler.asp?id=115984&titulo=saude in
Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY.

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil showing the
location of Sergipe state can be accessed at
http://healthmap.org/r/00T_. - Mod. TY]

- Brazil (Mato Grosso do Sul state). 12 Jul 2011. So far in 2011, 12
840 dengue cases have been reported in Mato Grosso do Sul. In total,
[dengue] 3 deaths were confirmed 2 in Campo Grande and one in
Paranaiba.
http://www.anastacionoticias.com.br/index.php?pagina=noticias-ver&codigo_noticia=26216
in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY.

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil showing the
location of Mato Grosso do Sul state can be accessed at
http://healthmap.org/r/01ay. - Mod.TY]

Asia
---
- Philippines (Batanes and national). 11 Jul 2011. The Department of
Health (DOH) has declared a dengue outbreak in 5 of 6 municipalities
in Batanes. The DOH has reported one death due to dengue and 901 cases
(as of 25 Jun 2011) compared to only 1 case last year [2010], said
DOH-National Epidemiology chief Dr Eric Tayag. The municipalities
affected are Sabtang (63 cases), Basco (487 cases), Mahatao (18),
Uyugan (47), and Itbayat (286). From 1 Jan-25 Jun [2011], there were
29 898 cases and 185 deaths in the country, 11 per cent lower than in
the same period last year [2010], which recorded 33 659 cases and 288
deaths.
http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/07/11/11/dengue-outbreak-declared-batanes.

[A map showing the location of Batanes Islands and Province can be
accessed at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batanes and the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Philippines can be seen
at http://healthmap.org/r/13uc. - Mod.TY]
